{"id":"1502.07196","submitter":"Asaf Farhi Mr.","authors":"Asaf Farhi","title":"Calculation of molecular free energies in classical potentials","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1367-2630/18/2/023039","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Free energies of molecules can be calculated by quantum computations or by\nnormal mode classical calculations. However, the first can be computationally\nimpractical for large molecules and the second is based on the assumption of\nharmonic dynamics. We present a novel, accurate and complete calculation of\nmolecular free energies in standard classical potentials. In this method we\ntransform the molecule by relaxing potential terms which depend on the\ncoordinates of a group of atoms in that molecule and calculate the free energy\ndifference associated with the transformation. Then, since the transformed\nmolecule can be treated as non interacting systems, the free energy associated\nwith these atoms is analytically or numerically calculated. This two-step\ncalculation can be applied to calculate free energies of molecules or free\nenergy difference between (possibly large) molecules in a general environment.\nWe suggest the potential application of free energy calculation of chemical\nreactions in classical molecular simulations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 23 Feb 2015 17:37:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 5 Apr 2015 16:44:53 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 8 Jul 2015 15:34:38 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Thu, 16 Jul 2015 16:03:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-23"}
